                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="13730" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Sun, 3 Jul 2005 16:59:33 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Well, nested properties can make sense in this context as well: nothing stops you from populating a nested configuration property on a bean. This also imposes an issue with backwards compatibility if we change the behavior here.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I would generally recommend to &lt;em&gt;not&lt;/em&gt; use dots in bean names. Use underscores or any other separator instead, to avoid conflicts with the property notation...&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13734" author="roland.huss" created="Sun, 3 Jul 2005 18:11:39 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I agree, that nested properties make sense indeed.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;However restricting bean names not use dots is a bit to restrictive IMHO. It&apos;s probably ok in certain circumstances to give a bean name some semantic meaning, but I don&apos;t see any use case for using a bean&apos;s identififier to point to some properties via a dot notation. Personally, I like dots to define separate namespaces related to the bean&apos;s java package.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I think a better solution would be to let the separator between the bean name and the property to be configurable in PropertyOverrideConfigurer (with default value &apos;.&apos;). This would keep backwards compatibility and doesn&apos;t restrict naming.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="13741" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Mon, 4 Jul 2005 07:15:57 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Good idea! I&apos;ve added a corresponding &quot;beanNameSeparator&quot; property to PropertyOverrideConfigurer, with a dot as default.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
